{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"764b4e6ee786c8160cd3eaafa70b00d55884c6eaab7faf0a3c846406ab9222af","slug":"index","location":"/docs/intro.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Introduction","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"nameParsed":{"literal":"Lukas Hörtnagl","given":"Lukas","family":"Hörtnagl"},"name":"Lukas Hörtnagl","email":"lukas.hoertnagl@usys.ethz.ch","affiliations":["ETH Zürich"],"id":"contributors-dev\\manuscripts\\ms-timelag-comparison\\myst-generated-uid-0","corresponding":true}],"affiliations":[{"id":"ETH Zürich","name":"ETH Zürich"}],"exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"intro.md","url":"/ms-timelag-comparison/build/intro-f2a9f6d731a2667d2a95dce5e5b21c08.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"This book documents the analysis for the manuscript on the impact of different\ntime-lag settings on eddy covariance fluxes of N₂O and CH₄.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"i1RwhCmL72"}],"key":"HQixu4cpDO"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":1},"end":{"line":12,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In eddy covariance, the time lag between the vertical wind measured by the sonic\nanemometer and the gas signal from the analyzer must be determined before fluxes\ncan be computed. How that lag is found can change the resulting flux: a wide\ncovariance-maximization search, a search with a default fallback, a fixed\nconstant lag, and an external detection method do not all give the same answer.\nThis study quantifies that effect by computing the fluxes several times from the\nsame raw data, varying only the time-lag setting, and comparing the results.","position":{"start":{"line":6,"column":1},"end":{"line":6,"column":1}},"key":"I3W2TMTKTy"}],"key":"HoqbK31xOb"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":